<h1>Expanding to European Marketplaces: Guide for Ukrainian Sellers</h1>
</section>

<article class="article-body">

<p>The European Union is the world's second-largest e-commerce market, with online retail sales exceeding 600 billion euros annually. For Ukrainian businesses with competitive products, the EU represents an enormous growth opportunity, one that has become increasingly accessible thanks to trade liberalization, improved logistics corridors, and platforms that actively welcome cross-border sellers. But accessing this market requires more than just listing products on Amazon. It demands an understanding of compliance requirements, cross-border logistics, marketplace-specific strategies, and the fulfillment infrastructure needed to compete with local European sellers.</p>

<p>This guide walks Ukrainian e-commerce businesses through the practical steps of expanding to European marketplaces, with a focus on Amazon, eBay, and Etsy, and explains how a domestic fulfillment partner like MTP Group can serve as the operational foundation for your cross-border ambitions.</p>

<h2>Why European Marketplaces Make Sense for Ukrainian Sellers</h2>

<p>Several converging factors make 2025-2026 an especially favorable window for Ukrainian businesses to enter European markets.</p>

<p><strong>Trade liberalization:</strong> Since June 2022, the EU has granted Ukraine autonomous trade measures that eliminate tariffs and quotas on most Ukrainian exports. Combined with Ukraine's EU candidate status and ongoing approximation to EU standards, the regulatory environment for cross-border commerce is becoming progressively simpler. Many product categories that previously faced import duties now enter the EU duty-free or at significantly reduced rates.</p>

<p><strong>Cost advantage:</strong> Ukrainian manufacturing and labor costs remain substantially lower than Western European equivalents. This means Ukrainian sellers can offer competitive prices on EU marketplaces while maintaining healthy margins. Whether you produce your own goods or source domestically, the cost structure works in your favor.</p>

<p><strong>Consumer sympathy and awareness:</strong> The war has dramatically increased European awareness of Ukraine. Many EU consumers actively seek out Ukrainian products as a form of support. This goodwill creates a marketing advantage that purely commercial sellers from other countries do not enjoy.</p>

<p><strong>Marketplace infrastructure:</strong> Amazon, eBay, and Etsy have all simplified their onboarding processes for cross-border sellers. Amazon's European Marketplace Unification allows you to list across Germany, France, Italy, Spain, the Netherlands, Poland, Sweden, and Belgium from a single seller account. eBay's Global Shipping Program handles customs for international sellers. Etsy has long been cross-border by design.</p>

<h2>Choosing the Right Marketplace</h2>

<p>Not every European marketplace is the right fit for every product. Understanding the strengths and audience of each platform helps you allocate resources effectively.</p>

<h3>Amazon Europe</h3>

<p>Amazon is the dominant general-purpose marketplace in the EU, particularly strong in Germany (amazon.de), France (amazon.fr), Italy (amazon.it), and Spain (amazon.es). Amazon Poland (amazon.pl) is growing rapidly and represents a natural entry point for Ukrainian sellers due to geographic proximity and lower competition compared to Western European markets.</p>

<p>Amazon is best suited for sellers offering branded or private-label consumer goods: electronics accessories, home and kitchen products, beauty and personal care, sports equipment, and pet supplies. The platform rewards competitive pricing, fast shipping, and strong product reviews. Amazon's FBA (Fulfillment by Amazon) service allows you to ship inventory to Amazon's EU warehouses, where they handle picking, packing, and delivery, but this requires advance investment in EU-positioned inventory.</p>

<h3>eBay Europe</h3>

<p>eBay remains a strong platform for niche products, collectibles, automotive parts, refurbished electronics, and any category where buyers are willing to wait slightly longer for delivery. eBay's seller protections for cross-border transactions are robust, and the platform's auction format can work well for unique or limited-quantity items.</p>

<p>For Ukrainian sellers, eBay's advantage is lower barriers to entry. You can start selling internationally from Ukraine without pre-positioning inventory in the EU. The Global Shipping Program handles customs and delivery logistics, though at the cost of longer delivery times and higher final prices for buyers.</p>

<h3>Etsy Europe</h3>

<p>Etsy is the platform of choice for handmade goods, vintage items, craft supplies, and artisanal products. Ukrainian sellers have had notable success on Etsy with embroidered clothing (vyshyvanky), handmade ceramics, jewelry, candles, natural cosmetics, and traditional Ukrainian crafts. The platform's audience actively seeks unique, culturally authentic products, and Ukrainian makers fit this demand perfectly.</p>

<p>Etsy requires no pre-positioned inventory and supports international shipping directly from your location. However, shipping speed and cost are significant competitive factors. Buyers expect trackable shipping and reasonable delivery windows, typically 7-14 business days for cross-border orders.</p>

<h2>Compliance Requirements You Cannot Ignore</h2>

<p>Selling into the EU comes with regulatory obligations that Ukrainian businesses must address before listing their first product. Ignoring these requirements can result in account suspension, product seizure at customs, or legal liability.</p>

<p><strong>CE marking:</strong> Many product categories sold in the EU require CE marking, a declaration that the product meets EU safety, health, and environmental protection standards. This applies to electronics, toys, personal protective equipment, medical devices, construction products, and more. CE marking is not a quality mark from a testing lab; it is the manufacturer's own declaration of conformity, but it must be backed by appropriate testing and technical documentation.</p>

<p><strong>REACH compliance:</strong> The EU's chemical regulation framework (REACH) governs the use of chemical substances in products. If your goods contain chemicals, dyes, coatings, or plastics, you may need to verify compliance with REACH restrictions. This is particularly relevant for cosmetics, textiles, and children's products.</p>

<p><strong>Product safety directives:</strong> The EU has specific directives for electrical products (Low Voltage Directive), electromagnetic compatibility (EMC Directive), toys, food contact materials, and numerous other categories. Your product must comply with all applicable directives, and you must maintain a technical file as evidence of conformity.</p>

<p><strong>EU Responsible Person:</strong> Since July 2021, all non-EU manufacturers selling products in the European Union must designate an EU-based Responsible Person. This individual or company is listed on the product or packaging and serves as the EU point of contact for market surveillance authorities. Several service providers in Poland, Germany, and the Netherlands offer Responsible Person services for Ukrainian businesses at costs of 50-200 euros per month depending on the number of products.</p>

<p><strong>VAT registration:</strong> If you store goods in an EU country (for example, using Amazon FBA), you are required to register for VAT in that country. Even without stored inventory, the EU's Import One-Stop Shop (IOSS) scheme simplifies VAT collection for goods valued under 150 euros shipped directly from outside the EU. Registering for IOSS allows you to charge VAT at the point of sale and remit it through a single EU member state, avoiding complex customs VAT procedures for buyers.</p>

<p><strong>EORI number:</strong> An Economic Operators Registration and Identification (EORI) number is required for any business importing goods into the EU. You can obtain an EORI number by registering with the customs authority of any EU member state. The process is free and typically takes 1-3 business days.</p>

<h2>Cross-Border Logistics: The Operational Challenge</h2>

<p>The biggest practical barrier to selling on European marketplaces is not compliance or listing optimization. It is logistics. European consumers expect fast, trackable, and affordable shipping. Competing with local EU sellers who offer next-day delivery through Amazon Prime or domestic postal services requires a deliberate logistics strategy.</p>

<p>Ukrainian sellers generally have three logistics models available:</p>

<p><strong>Direct shipping from Ukraine:</strong> The simplest model. Orders are packed in Ukraine and shipped directly to European buyers via international postal services (Ukrposhta, Meest, or DHL/UPS for express). Delivery times range from 5 to 14 business days depending on the destination and service level. This model requires no EU inventory positioning and has the lowest upfront cost, but it limits your competitiveness on speed-sensitive platforms like Amazon.</p>

<p><strong>Bulk export to EU fulfillment centers:</strong> You ship inventory in bulk to a fulfillment center located in the EU (Amazon FBA or a third-party EU warehouse). Orders are then fulfilled locally within the EU with 1-3 day delivery times. This model maximizes competitiveness but requires upfront inventory investment, VAT registration, and higher storage costs at EU rates.</p>

<p><strong>Hybrid model with domestic consolidation:</strong> This is where a Ukrainian fulfillment partner becomes critical. Instead of managing export logistics yourself, you send inventory to MTP Group's warehouse. MTP Group handles consolidation, export-grade packaging, customs documentation preparation, and handoff to international carriers. Batch shipments go to EU fulfillment centers on a regular schedule, while urgent or small orders can be shipped directly to end customers.</p>

<h2>How MTP Group Enables EU Marketplace Expansion</h2>

<p>MTP Group's role in a cross-border logistics strategy is to serve as your domestic operations hub: the single point where all inventory arrives, is processed, quality-checked, and then routed to its destination, whether that is a domestic Ukrainian customer via Nova Poshta, an Amazon FBA warehouse in Poland, or a direct international shipment to a buyer in Germany.</p>

<p>Here is what MTP Group provides for sellers expanding to European marketplaces:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Inventory consolidation:</strong> Receive goods from multiple suppliers at MTP Group's warehouse, inspect quality, and consolidate into export-ready batches. This eliminates the need for you to handle physical inventory before it goes international.</li>
<li><strong>Export packaging:</strong> International shipments require more robust packaging than domestic orders. MTP Group packs export batches to withstand longer transit times, multiple handling points, and customs inspection. Palletization, strapping, and proper labeling are handled to carrier and warehouse standards.</li>
<li><strong>Documentation support:</strong> While customs brokerage itself is handled by specialized agents, MTP Group prepares the commercial invoices, packing lists, and product descriptions needed for customs clearance. Having accurate, pre-prepared documentation significantly reduces the risk of shipment delays at the border.</li>
